🎅🏼Christmas Candy Cane Danish! 
Easiest recipe around, the kind I love and your guests will be impressed because it’s delicious!!! 
All you need is…
*One can of croissants 
*Whipped cream cheese
*Smuckers Jelly (I used raspberry) 
*Powdered sugar

Spread the croissant dough out piece by piece in a rounded candy cane shape. 
Spread the cream cheese out (I use the back of a table spoon for an easy spread) onto the thick part of the cane. 
Spread the raspberry jelly on top of the cream cheese.
Fold the croissants over to form the candy cane. 
Put into the oven, bake on 350 for 12-15 minutes. 
Sift some powdered sugar on top of the candy cane and you’re done. 

It’s flaky and delicious! ENJOY!!!!!

New Orleans is already rich in culture, diversity and history so when @hotelmonteleone reached out and asked me to stay with them, the answer was obvious! 
Hotel Monteleone is one of the last family owned hotels in the country and is one of only three hotels in the world to be declared a literary landmark! 
The hotel began in 1886 as The Commercial, later becoming Hotel Monteleone after the family’s name. 
It is home to the only rotating carousel bar! People begin lining up at 10:30 in the morning to get a seat! 
The Vieux Carré is the Carousel Bar’s most famous cocktail. Created in 1938 by Hotel Monteleone’s head bartender, Walter Bergeron, it consists of Cognac, Benedictine, Rye Whiskey, Sweet Vermouth, Angostura, and Peychaud’s Bitters. My favorite is their Pims Cup made with Gin, Strawberries, Cucumber, Lemon Juice, Simple Syrup, and Sprite.

I felt so lucky today to get to sit down and have lunch with Lisa at @antoinesnola She is married to a fifth generation Antoine, of the Antoine’s restaurant legacy and is as spunky as she is sweet. She immediately made us feel at home and so comfortable! I love how invested and genuinely passionate she is, not only about the Antoine family and it’s legacy, but about the restaurant itself! 

Antoine’s is a traditional New Orleans restaurant. Opening its restaurant doors in 1870, makes it New Orleans oldest restaurant. Did you know that before 1870, restaurants did not exist, not in the sense of people going to a certain place, sitting down and waiters taking their orders and eating? Also, and I love this new fact I learned, that when people wanted to go and eat at a restaurant, they used to have to handwrite letters and request to come and eat, it was a very formal part of dinning. 

Antoine’s is one restaurant that you want to visit, not only for its rich history but for the food, it a true taste of Nola. 
Today for lunch we had  these dishes and would highly recommend them;
* Oysters Bienville
Baked with white wine, green onions, fresh peppers, pimentos, grated Romano cheese.
* Antoine's Chilled Seafood Duo
Classic duo of shrimp remoulade and crabmeat ravigote.
* Pompano Pontchartrain
Grilled pompano filet, butter poached jumbo lump crabmeat, white wine reduction, onion rice.
*Strawberry salad and their delicious French dip. {there is nothing better than New Orleans French bread!}
Last we had their Antoine's Pecan Bread Pudding
Leidenheimer French bread, eggs, cream, cinnamon, vanilla, golden raisin, and butter rum sauce! 
Everything was delicious and we loved being able to get the history first hand!

I love being SOUTHERN and believe it or not there are  rules! None of these rules are written down. Southerners just absorb them through cornbread and the liquid sugarcane we call sweet tea. Here are some!!!! 

* Take off your hat or cap in the house, especially when eating or when a lady is present. 
* When friends come over, children should let their guests choose the games and the snacks. It teaches consideration and courtesy.
* Always send a thank-you note (not a text) for a gift.
* Always see your guests to the door when they leave.
* Always say please and thank you.
* Everybody holds the door open for whomever is approaching from behind you. "Southerners instinctively know if people are behind us when we're walking into stores, restaurants, and offices, and we patiently hold the door.
* Cancel plans only if there is an emergency (which does not involve Netflix and the sofa)
* Give your seat to people with disabilities, women who are expecting, and folks older than you.
* Never show up empty handed. When someone invites you over for dinner always bring a gift.

An easy dinner that delicious and pretty quick! Chicken in a Creamy White Wine Sauce. Great for company or just for two! Freezes well too! Bon Appetit! 🍽️

INGREDIENTS
* 1 tbsp olive oil
* 1 onion finely chopped
* 4-5 strips of bacon/pancetta chopped
* 4 garlic cloves thinly sliced
* 8 chicken pieces on the bone thighs and legs
* One cup of mushrooms whole or halved
* 500 ml/2/3 of a bottle of dry white wine such as Chardonnay or Sauvignon Blanc {Use a dry wine bc when wine is added to the dish it sweetens and you do not want a sweet dish}
*1 cup double/whipping cream
* salt & pepper to taste
* handful flat leaf chopped parsley

INSTRUCTIONS
* Cook bacon or pancetta in a tablespoon of olive oil. Skip oil if bacon is too fatty. Remove the bacon to a paper towel-lined plate.
* Salt and pepper the chicken pieces and brown them in bacon fat over medium-high heat. Remove to a paper towel-lined plate.
* Cook chopped onion over low heat for 5-7 minutes, add garlic when the onion is tender and translucent and cook for 1 minute longer. Remove cooked onion and garlic to the same plate as chicken and bacon.
* Add mushrooms to the pan and brown them for 3-5 minutes over medium-high heat.
* Return chicken, onion, garlic and bacon to the pan, pour wine all over, bring to a boil, then lower the heat to low and simmer for 40 minutes.
* Add cream and simmer for 10 minutes longer.
* Sprinkle with chopped parsley before serving.
* Serve with mashed potatoes or rice and crusty bread to mop up all that amazing sauce.

So excited that college football season will be starting! One of my favorite things to do is tailgate! Whether you are tailgating in the stadium parking lot or in your driveway with neighbors there are several rules to follow! 
1. Either have others bring their own chairs or have plenty of folding chairs to sit in. 
2. Decorate like crazy! You can never have too much. It’s also easy to find solid color beads and Pom poms…and things like that from @partycity to throw in. 
3. Make finger foods or easy to serve foods. Things that can be pre-prepped so that you can also enjoy your time too! 
4. Have lots of ice with waters, drinks and some non-alcoholic beverages. 
5. Have a big movie screen that you can project the game onto or a big tv! 
6. Have a couple of things for others to do, like bocce ball, corn hole or a large Jenga game. 
7. Have plenty of trash bags and paper towels around. 
8. Incorporate a small keepsake for each person or couple to take home to remember their time at the big game! Photo Booth with Polaroids, or even a little to-go box with sweet treats for later.

CHICKEN PASTA SALAD RECIPE
* 2 medium cooked chicken breasts, shredded or chopped {I used rotisserie chicken already pulled off the bone from the grocery}
* 2 ripe avocado pitted and diced
* 1 pound cooked rotini pasta or similar
* 1/2 cup chopped red onion
* 1 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
* 1/2 cup freshly chopped basil
* Salt and fresh cracked pepper, to taste
Dressing
* 1/2 cup white wine vinegar
* 1 tablespoon Italian seasoning
* 3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
* Salt and pepper 

DIRECTIONS
1. To make this healthy chicken pasta salad recipe: In a large bowl, add the salad ingredients, the shredded chicken, pasta, onion, avocado, cherry tomatoes, and basil.
2. In a jar, combine the ingredients for the dressing: vinegar, Italian seasoning, Olive oil, salt and pepper.
3. Drizzle your chicken pasta salad with the dressing. Toss gently until all the ingredients are combined. Serve the chicken pasta salad immediately, or chill for later. Enjoy!

My top 10 things to see when visiting the San Francisco  Bay Area!

9. Explore Fisherman’s Wharf
Fisherman’s Wharf is probably the most visited neighborhood in San Francisco. This small neighborhood has bars, restaurants and shops! Make sure to check out the Pier Market Seafood Restaurant.

Located right on Fisherman’s Wharf, is the Boudin Bakery. This iconic bakery is famous for its delicious sourdough bread. Mmm!
7.  Watch the Sea Lions Bicker at Pier 39. The docks at Pier 39 are a favorite napping spot for the local Sea Lions. It’s quite comical to watch these creatures as they tend to pick fights with their neighbors! 
6.  Visit China Town
You’ll feel transported to another country when you step foot into China Town. Almost immediately, the language on every sign changes from English to Chinese and the building architecture takes on a different vibe too. 
5. Have a Picnic at Alamo Square Park! The Painted Ladies are probably some of the most recognized homes in America. They’re most known from the beloved TV show, Full House. Although, it’s not as commonly known that none of these houses were the actual house featured in Full House. The actual house in Full House can be found at 1709 Broderick St. in San Francisco.
4. Muir Woods National Monument
California’s Redwoods are famously known for being the tallest trees in the world. It’s absolutely gorgeous. 
3. The Buena Vista! Stop in and get their famous baileys and coffee! 
2. Visit Sausalito! It is the most quaint town I have ever seen. Full of shops, restaurants and marinas! Gorgeous.

 Ingredients

milk or cream

2 Tbs. white nonpareils
⚡️Witch Hat & Stirring Spoon Ingredients
12 chocolate drops

12 pretzel sticks

⚡️Bake Brownies normally but put them into muffin tins. 
For a quick frosting just buy a store bought yummy chocolate frosting or you can make your own. 

⚡️Fill Cauldrons
Fill the divot in each brownie with about 2 tablespoons of icing using two spoons. Gently coax a little of the icing over one side, as if the frosting is spilling over the brownie’s top edge. Immediately sprinkle the freshly frosted brownie with green sugar pearls, then finish with a sprinkle of white nonpareils. Reserve the leftover icing. Set aside and gather the ingredients for the witch hats.
⚡️Assemble Witch Hats
Place an oreo cookie on a plate and top with a small dollop of icing in the center, about 1/2 teaspoon. Place a chocolate drop on top of the frosting and press down until the frosting squeezes out around the edges of the chocolate. Wrap a length of sour candy lace around the bottom edge of the chocolate drop and trim using scissors.

Do you know what a Love Language is? It is the way someone perceives, shows and needs love. 
If you’ve looked into improving your relationship with your partner, chances are you’ve heard of the five love languages. The theory— was published by marriage counselor Gary Chapman, Ph.D., in his book The 5 Love Languages: proposes that people experience love differently. 
Dr. Chapman identifies five categories through which people receive and express love, including words of 1. affirmation 2. acts of service 3. receiving gifts 4. quality time and 5. physical touch.
They studied unsatisfied marriages for years and discovered that people fit into one of those 5 categories. 9 out 10 times their partner had no idea what they were really needing. But, he says…if they were watching the way their partner showed love to others and listened to what they complained about not getting, they would know! 
An example would be: if a husband’s love language is acts of service, he may be confused when he does the laundry and his wife does not perceive that as an act of love, viewing it as simply performing household duties, because the love language she comprehends is words of affirmation (verbal affirmation that he loves her). 

Here are the five Love Languages. 
1. Words of Affirmation
This love language consists of encouraging, positive words and verbal or written acknowledgments of love and care.
2. Acts of Service
For those with this love language, a helping hand makes them feel cared for, and doing something to lighten their load will go a long way. Dishes, laundry, filling the gas tank up. 
3. Receiving Gifts 
It’s the thought that counts, not the price of the gift, says Lurie. People with this love language appreciate receiving a visual symbol of their partner’s affection—especially one that’s been carefully selected by the giver. 
4. Quality Time 
That means making your partner feel like they’re a priority by turning the phone off, not engaging in distractions, making eye contact, sitting close and using active listening skills. 
5. Physical Touch
People who are a part of this group need to be touched, hugged, and kissed to feel bonded with their partner. Most men are here.
